[{"sha":"22b8e15e87f452d15084b8964a1bf9e3e9c6ccb1","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Support collectives in RemoteCall

CollectiveExecutor was only available if collective graph key is set. TF2 in combination with collective v2 doesn't really have the concept of collective graph key. In the past a workaround was added to set the graph key to a magic number of v2 ops are present. This is not very maintainable as we are adding more collective ops. It also doesn't cover the case of functional ops.

This changes makes CollectiveExecutor always available.

[{"sha":"a985655ac4eb6c5b60b5eab8d8d09a487e353e1d","author":{"name":"Tianon Gravi","email":"4b2b69742da531f1900c4c4748d7a0ecda59626a@gmail.com"},"message":"Move containerd.service from Requires= to Wants=

Per the systemd.unit documentation:

> If this unit gets activated, the units listed will be activated as well. If one of the other units fails to activate, and an ordering dependency After= on the failing unit is set, this unit will not be started. Besides, with or without specifying After=, this unit will be stopped if one of the other units is explicitly stopped.
>
> Often, it is a better choice to use Wants= instead of Requires= in order to achieve a system that is more robust when dealing with failing services.

This should also be generally "safe" given we added `--containerd=/run/containerd/containerd.sock` to the flags we pass to `dockerd`.

In legacy roots, if an update originates outside of `batchedUpdates`,
check if it's inside an `act` scope; if so, treat it as if it were
batched. This is only necessary in legacy roots because in concurrent
roots, updates are batched by default.

With this change, the Test Utils and Test Renderer versions of `act` are
nothing more than aliases of the isomorphic API (still not exposed, but
will likely be the recommended API that replaces the others).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/a4ecd85e8628d1fdfe77c5615934de40af7d9537"}]

Add the following operations to the TF framework dialect:

- `JITCompileOp` to express regions with TF ops that shall be JIT compiled on
  on first use.

- `JITCompileFromStrOp` to express JIT compilation based on a serialized module.
- `JITExecuteOp` to express the invocation of a JIT-compiled callable.

Change-Id: Ic9d65c8672990cc0f078bc593f4b7a2a4cd00faf","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/baae32dea974ba2ab26fd20b34695653b4e2a1e8"},{"sha":"0f8115e4e29474faeee384edaf352523d8bec4b3","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add (AssignVariable)XlaConcatND op.

This op takes multiple input slices (row major order), slices out right paddings from the slices, and concats all slices based on concats per dimension across all dimensions.

Currently in the TPU bridge, a tree of Concat ops (with Slice ops potentially) is created to merge shard inputs. This can create temporary memory allocations at each level of Concat ops. Fusing these operations into 1 op removes these temporary allocations, reducing some memory overhead.

A resource variable assign/update version is also created, to remove an extra potential copying of the input tensor.

Inverse of (ReadVariable)XlaSplitND op.

We previously built out addrs.UnifyMoveEndpoints with a different
implementation strategy in mind, but that design turns out to not be
viable because it forces us to move to AbsMoveable addresses too soon,

we found a good scenario for ppc64le, where gemm_pack_rhs from TF headers
together with VSX/MMA from ppc64le speeds up the performance of convolution.

and disables the Eigen ppc64le gemm_pack_rhs using the define

Many times now we've seen situations where we need to use addresses
as map keys, but not all of our address types are comparable and thus
we tend to end up using string representations as keys instead.

That's problematic because conversion to string uses type information
and some of the address types have string representations that are
ambiguous with one another.

UniqueKey therefore represents an opaque key that is unique for each
functionally-distinct address across all types that implement
UniqueKeyer.

For this initial commit I've implemented UniqueKeyer only for the
Referenceable family of types. These are an easy case because they
were all already comparable (intentionally) anyway. Later commits
can implement UniqueKeyer for other types that are not naturally
comparable, such as any which include a ModuleInstance.

This also includes a new type addrs.Set which wraps a map as a set
of addresses, using the unique keys to ensure that there can be only
one element for each distinct address.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8028324b99310a8d9bcd5cb7859ad92f379dd00e"},{"sha":"fd4bbd3d9d0da2a205a2e9f7b9883856bf047c79","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: ModuleInstance and AbsResourceInstance are UniqueKeyers

an unexported named type around the string representation, whereby the

different types and thus each type only needs to worry about possible

We previously built out addrs.UnifyMoveEndpoints with a different
implementation strategy in mind, but that design turns out to not be
viable because it forces us to move to AbsMoveable addresses too soon,
before we've done the analysis required to identify chained and nested
moves.

Instead, UnifyMoveEndpoints will return a new type MoveEndpointInModule
which conceptually represents a matching pattern which either matches or
doesn't match a particular AbsMoveable. It does this by just binding the
unified relative address from the MoveEndpoint to the module where it
was declared, and thus allows us to distinguish between the part of the
module path which applies to any instances of the given modules vs. the
